CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Cloud Deployment Models", body:"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>deployment model</span> describes <em>who owns, operates, and consumes</em> a cloud environment. It is distinct from a service model (IaaS, PaaS, SaaS), which describes how much of the stack the provider manages. CV0-004 expects you to classify a scenario into the correct deployment model from the wording around ownership, tenancy, and who shares the infrastructure. The four canonical models are public, private, hybrid, and community, and most real enterprises end up with a blend.</p><h3>Public cloud</h3><p>In the <span class='keyterm'>public cloud</span> a third-party provider (AWS, Azure, Google Cloud) owns the physical infrastructure and rents it to many unrelated customers over the internet. The defining trait is <strong>multitenancy</strong>: your workloads share physical hardware with other organizations, isolated by the hypervisor and software-defined networking. Public cloud delivers the purest <em>pay-as-you-go</em> economics and near-infinite elasticity, but you surrender control over the physical layer and accept the provider's shared-responsibility boundary. It is the default choice for variable workloads, startups, and any team that wants to trade capital expenditure for operating expenditure.</p><h3>Private cloud (on-premises)</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>private cloud</span> is dedicated to a single organization. It can sit in your own data center (on-premises) or be hosted by a provider as a single-tenant environment, but the resources are never shared with outsiders. Private cloud is built with platforms such as VMware vSphere/vCloud, OpenStack, or Azure Stack, and it preserves the self-service, elastic, automated character of cloud while keeping data and hardware under direct control. Organizations choose private cloud for strict regulatory mandates, predictable steady-state workloads where owned hardware is cheaper, or latency-sensitive systems that must stay close to on-site equipment. The trade-off is that you fund and operate the capacity yourself, so true elasticity is bounded by what you bought.</p><h3>Hybrid cloud</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>hybrid cloud</span> deliberately connects a private environment with one or more public clouds so workloads and data can move between them, usually over a VPN or a dedicated circuit such as AWS Direct Connect or Azure ExpressRoute. The classic hybrid pattern is <strong>cloud bursting</strong>: steady demand runs on owned private capacity, and overflow spills into the public cloud during peaks. Hybrid lets an organization keep regulated data on-premises while using public elasticity for the front end, but it introduces integration complexity, identity federation challenges, and a network seam that must be secured and monitored.</p><h3>Community cloud</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>community cloud</span> is shared by several organizations with a common concern - the same regulatory regime, mission, or security requirements. Examples include a healthcare consortium sharing a HIPAA-aligned platform, or government agencies on a FedRAMP-authorized environment such as AWS GovCloud. Costs and governance are split among the member organizations, which makes it cheaper than a private cloud for each member while keeping the tenant pool restricted to trusted peers - a middle ground between public openness and private exclusivity.</p><h3>Multicloud and the model spectrum</h3><p>Beyond the four NIST-style models, modern practice adds <span class='keyterm'>multicloud</span> - the deliberate use of services from two or more <em>public</em> providers at once. Multicloud is not a fifth deployment model on the exam but a strategy layered on top: an organization might run analytics on Google BigQuery, identity on Microsoft Entra, and compute on AWS. The motivation is to avoid single-vendor lock-in, exploit each provider's best-of-breed service, and improve resilience against a single provider's regional outage. The cost is operational complexity: separate IAM models, separate billing, separate tooling, and engineers who must be fluent in multiple consoles. Be careful to distinguish multicloud (several public clouds) from hybrid (private plus public); the exam tests this boundary directly.</p><h3>The shared responsibility boundary by model</h3><p>Each deployment model shifts the <span class='keyterm'>shared responsibility</span> line. In public cloud the provider secures the physical facility, hypervisor, and core network, while you secure your data, identities, and configuration. In a self-hosted private cloud you own the <em>entire</em> stack from concrete to application, which is maximum control but maximum burden. Hybrid splits responsibility across the seam - you own the on-prem half outright and share the public half - which is why the connecting VPN or dedicated circuit becomes a critical security control. Community cloud distributes responsibility among the consortium and the hosting provider, often formalized in a shared governance charter so no member's lax configuration endangers the others.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>You secure</th><th>Provider secures</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Public</td><td>Data, IAM, config, app</td><td>Facility, hypervisor, network fabric</td></tr><tr><td>Private (self-hosted)</td><td>Everything</td><td>Nothing (you are the provider)</td></tr><tr><td>Hybrid</td><td>On-prem fully + cloud config</td><td>Public-side physical layer</td></tr><tr><td>Community</td><td>Member's own tenancy</td><td>Shared platform layer</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Cost models compared</h3><p>The deployment model also dictates the financial shape. Public cloud is almost entirely <span class='keyterm'>operating expenditure</span> (OpEx) - you pay per hour, per gigabyte, per request, with no upfront capital. Private cloud is dominated by <span class='keyterm'>capital expenditure</span> (CapEx) - large upfront hardware purchases depreciated over years - plus ongoing power, cooling, and staff. The classic decision rule is that steady, predictable, high-utilization workloads often favor owned CapEx capacity, while spiky or uncertain workloads favor public OpEx because you never pay for idle hardware. Hybrid lets a firm place each workload on the side where its cost curve is cheapest, which is a major reason hybrid endures despite its complexity.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A university runs its student information system on owned hardware in its data center for cost predictability and data control, but offloads end-of-term grade-processing spikes and a public course catalog to AWS. Steady internal load stays private; elastic bursts and public-facing assets go to the public cloud across a Direct Connect link. The result is textbook hybrid, chosen because each workload's cost and compliance profile points to a different side of the seam.</p></div><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Tenancy</th><th>Owner/operator</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Public</td><td>Many unrelated tenants</td><td>Cloud provider</td><td>Variable, bursty, cost-flexible workloads</td></tr><tr><td>Private</td><td>Single organization</td><td>You or a dedicated host</td><td>Strict control, regulation, steady load</td></tr><tr><td>Hybrid</td><td>Mixed private + public</td><td>Shared boundary</td><td>Bursting, data residency + elasticity</td></tr><tr><td>Community</td><td>Several aligned orgs</td><td>The member group</td><td>Shared compliance or mission</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Read for <em>who shares the hardware</em>. One company only = private. Anyone on the internet = public. A connected mix that lets workloads move = hybrid. A closed group with a shared mandate (e.g., several hospitals under HIPAA) = community. \"On-premises\" by itself usually signals private, but a private cloud can also be provider-hosted as single-tenant.</p></div><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>Students conflate deployment model with service model: a private cloud can still offer IaaS, PaaS, or SaaS internally. Another trap is assuming on-premises always means private - a co-located, provider-managed single-tenant rack is still private cloud. Finally, hybrid is not simply \"using two clouds\"; that is multicloud. Hybrid specifically pairs a private environment with public capacity across an integrated boundary.</p>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Deployment Strategies: Blue-Green and Canary", body:"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>deployment strategy</span> governs how a new version of an application replaces the running one while minimizing downtime and risk. CV0-004 expects fluency in four named strategies - blue-green, canary, rolling, and in-place - including when to choose each and how rollback works. This section covers the two that rely on running two versions side by side; the next covers the two that mutate capacity in place.</p><h3>Blue-green deployment</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>blue-green deployment</span> maintains two complete, identical production environments. <strong>Blue</strong> is the version currently serving traffic; <strong>green</strong> is the new version, fully deployed and validated in parallel but receiving no live traffic. The cutover is a single switch at the load balancer or DNS layer that redirects all users from blue to green at once. The headline benefit is <em>instant rollback</em>: if green misbehaves, you flip traffic back to blue, which is still running and untouched. The cost is that you must run double the production capacity during the transition, and any database schema changes must be backward-compatible so both versions can share state during the swap.</p><pre><code># Shift 100% of traffic to the green target group at once\naws elbv2 modify-listener \\\n  --listener-arn $LISTENER_ARN \\\n  --default-actions Type=forward,TargetGroupArn=$GREEN_TG_ARN\n\n# Rollback is just the inverse switch back to blue\naws elbv2 modify-listener \\\n  --listener-arn $LISTENER_ARN \\\n  --default-actions Type=forward,TargetGroupArn=$BLUE_TG_ARN</code></pre><h3>Canary deployment</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>canary deployment</span> exposes the new version to a small slice of real users first - often 1% to 5% - while everyone else stays on the old version. You watch error rates, latency, and business metrics for the canary cohort, and only if they hold do you progressively shift more traffic (5% to 25% to 50% to 100%). The name comes from the canary in a coal mine: a small early-warning population that fails before the whole fleet is at risk. Canary gives the most controlled <em>blast radius</em> of any strategy because a bad release harms only the small cohort, and automated analysis can halt or reverse the rollout the moment metrics degrade.</p><h3>Traffic shifting and weighted routing</h3><p>Both strategies depend on <span class='keyterm'>traffic shifting</span> - the ability to send a controlled percentage of requests to a specific version. This is implemented with weighted target groups, weighted DNS records (Route 53), or a service mesh (Istio, App Mesh) that splits traffic at the request level. Weighted routing is what makes a canary <em>progressive</em>: you raise the new version's weight in steps rather than all at once.</p><pre><code># Route 53 weighted records: 10% canary, 90% stable\nresource \"aws_route53_record\" \"canary\" {\n  zone_id        = var.zone_id\n  name           = \"app.example.com\"\n  type           = \"A\"\n  set_identifier = \"canary\"\n  weighted_routing_policy { weight = 10 }\n  alias { name = aws_lb.canary.dns_name\n          zone_id = aws_lb.canary.zone_id\n          evaluate_target_health = true }\n}</code></pre><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Blue-green</th><th>Canary</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Traffic cutover</td><td>All at once</td><td>Gradual, percentage-based</td></tr><tr><td>Rollback speed</td><td>Instant (flip back to blue)</td><td>Lower weight / halt rollout</td></tr><tr><td>Extra capacity</td><td>Full duplicate environment</td><td>Small additional cohort</td></tr><tr><td>Blast radius</td><td>All users if not caught fast</td><td>Only the canary cohort</td></tr><tr><td>Best when</td><td>You want zero-downtime swap + fast revert</td><td>You want to validate on real traffic safely</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Automated canary analysis</h3><p>Mature canary pipelines do not rely on a human staring at dashboards. They use <span class='keyterm'>automated canary analysis</span> (ACA): the pipeline collects metrics from the canary cohort and a baseline cohort, runs statistical comparisons, and emits a pass/fail score that gates each promotion step. Tools such as Spinnaker with Kayenta, Argo Rollouts, or Flagger drive this loop. The key inputs are <em>service-level indicators</em> - error rate, p95/p99 latency, saturation - compared against the stable version over the same window so that organic traffic variation does not produce a false verdict.</p><pre><code># Argo Rollouts canary with automated analysis gates\napiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1\nkind: Rollout\nspec:\n  strategy:\n    canary:\n      steps:\n        - setWeight: 5\n        - pause: { duration: 10m }\n        - analysis:\n            templates:\n              - templateName: success-rate\n        - setWeight: 25\n        - pause: { duration: 10m }\n        - setWeight: 50\n        - pause: { duration: 10m }\n        - setWeight: 100</code></pre><h3>The database compatibility problem</h3><p>The deepest pitfall in both strategies is the database. Because two application versions run concurrently, any schema change must be <strong>backward and forward compatible</strong> during the overlap. The standard discipline is the <span class='keyterm'>expand-contract</span> (parallel change) pattern: first <em>expand</em> the schema by adding the new column or table without removing the old, deploy code that writes to both and reads the new, then <em>contract</em> by dropping the obsolete column only after every instance runs the new version. Skipping this is the most common cause of a blue-green cutover that corrupts data the instant traffic flips.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Phase</th><th>Schema action</th><th>Code behavior</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Expand</td><td>Add new column/table</td><td>Old code ignores it; safe to deploy</td></tr><tr><td>Migrate</td><td>Backfill data</td><td>New code reads/writes both old and new</td></tr><tr><td>Contract</td><td>Drop old column</td><td>Only after all instances upgraded</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Feature flags as a complement</h3><p>A powerful refinement is to decouple <em>deployment</em> from <em>release</em> using <span class='keyterm'>feature flags</span>. The new code ships to all servers (a low-risk rolling or in-place deploy of dormant code), then the feature is switched on for a small percentage of users via a flag service such as LaunchDarkly. This achieves a canary-like progressive exposure without running two infrastructure versions, and it lets you kill a bad feature instantly with a config toggle rather than a redeploy. Flags also enable per-segment targeting - enable for internal staff first, then beta users, then everyone.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A payments team must ship a checkout rewrite with zero tolerance for a bad release reaching all customers. They deploy it as a canary at 2%, watch payment-success rate and latency for an hour, then step to 20%, 50%, and 100% over a day - aborting instantly if success rate dips. Canary fits because it limits blast radius and validates against genuine traffic.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A SaaS vendor must guarantee that if the new release is broken, recovery takes seconds, not minutes. They run blue-green: the green stack is fully warmed and load-tested behind a hidden listener, then the load balancer flips 100% of traffic to green in one API call. When green throws elevated 500s ten minutes later, one inverse call routes everyone back to the still-running blue stack - rollback in under a minute with no rebuild.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>If the scenario stresses <em>instant rollback</em> and a clean swap, choose blue-green. If it stresses <em>limiting risk by testing on a small subset of real users</em>, choose canary. Both require backward-compatible data changes because two versions run concurrently - remember expand-contract. Feature flags let you separate deploying code from releasing a feature.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Deployment Strategies: Rolling and In-Place", body:"<p>Where blue-green and canary run two versions in parallel, <span class='keyterm'>rolling</span> and <span class='keyterm'>in-place</span> deployments change the existing fleet directly. They use less extra capacity but offer slower or messier rollback, so understanding the trade-off is exactly what CV0-004 probes.</p><h3>Rolling deployment</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>rolling deployment</span> updates instances in batches rather than all at once. You take a subset out of the load-balancer rotation, update them to the new version, health-check them back in, then move to the next batch until the whole fleet is upgraded. During the rollout the fleet is <em>mixed</em>: some instances run the old version and some the new, so both must be compatible. The benefit is that you never need a full duplicate environment - you reuse the same capacity - and there is no downtime because the service stays up throughout. The downside is that rollback is slow: reverting means rolling the old version back across every batch, and a mixed-version window can surface subtle incompatibilities.</p><pre><code># Kubernetes rolling update: replace pods gradually\nspec:\n  strategy:\n    type: RollingUpdate\n    rollingUpdate:\n      maxSurge: 1          # one extra pod above desired count\n      maxUnavailable: 0    # never drop below desired during rollout\n  template:\n    spec:\n      containers:\n        - name: web\n          image: registry.example.com/web:v2.3.0</code></pre><p>The <code>maxSurge</code> and <code>maxUnavailable</code> knobs control the rollout's aggressiveness. Setting <code>maxUnavailable: 0</code> guarantees full capacity during the rollout at the cost of needing one extra pod's worth of headroom (<code>maxSurge: 1</code>).</p><h3>In-place deployment</h3><p>An <span class='keyterm'>in-place deployment</span> updates the application <em>on the same servers</em> without provisioning new ones - it stops the old version, installs the new code, and restarts the service on each existing host. It is the simplest and cheapest strategy because it needs no additional infrastructure, and it is common for stateful systems that are awkward to replace. The serious drawback is downtime or degraded service during the swap, and rollback requires reinstalling the prior version on each host, which is slower and more error-prone than flipping a load-balancer target. In-place also breaks the <span class='keyterm'>immutable infrastructure</span> ideal: servers are mutated and can drift over time.</p><pre><code># AWS CodeDeploy in-place spec: hooks run on each existing host\nversion: 0.0\nos: linux\nhooks:\n  ApplicationStop:\n    - location: scripts/stop_server.sh\n  AfterInstall:\n    - location: scripts/install_deps.sh\n  ApplicationStart:\n    - location: scripts/start_server.sh\n  ValidateService:\n    - location: scripts/health_check.sh</code></pre><table><thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Extra capacity</th><th>Downtime</th><th>Rollback</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Blue-green</td><td>Full duplicate</td><td>None</td><td>Instant</td><td>Critical apps needing fast revert</td></tr><tr><td>Canary</td><td>Small cohort</td><td>None</td><td>Reduce weight</td><td>Risk-limited validation on real users</td></tr><tr><td>Rolling</td><td>One batch</td><td>None</td><td>Slow (re-roll)</td><td>Large fleets, limited spare capacity</td></tr><tr><td>In-place</td><td>None</td><td>Some</td><td>Slowest (reinstall)</td><td>Cost-constrained, stateful, simple apps</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Health checks and gradual rollout control</h3><p>Rolling deployments live or die on their <span class='keyterm'>health checks</span>. After each batch updates, the orchestrator must confirm the new instances are genuinely healthy - not merely running, but passing a readiness probe that exercises real dependencies (database connectivity, downstream APIs) before the batch rejoins the load balancer. A shallow health check that only verifies the process is alive will happily march a broken release across the entire fleet. This is why Kubernetes distinguishes a <em>liveness</em> probe (restart if dead) from a <em>readiness</em> probe (withhold traffic until ready); a rolling update should pause on readiness failures.</p><pre><code># Readiness gate so a rolling update halts on a bad batch\nreadinessProbe:\n  httpGet:\n    path: /healthz\n    port: 8080\n  initialDelaySeconds: 10\n  periodSeconds: 5\n  failureThreshold: 3\nlivenessProbe:\n  httpGet:\n    path: /alive\n    port: 8080\n  periodSeconds: 10</code></pre><h3>In-place and configuration drift</h3><p>Because in-place mutates long-lived servers, it is the strategy most prone to <span class='keyterm'>configuration drift</span> - the slow divergence of a server from its intended state as successive hotfixes and manual tweaks accumulate. Two servers that started identical can, after a year of in-place patches, behave differently in ways nobody can fully reconstruct. The cloud-native antidote is <span class='keyterm'>immutable infrastructure</span>: rather than updating a server in place, you bake a new machine image (with Packer, for example), launch fresh instances from it, and terminate the old ones. This converts every deployment into a blue-green or rolling <em>replacement</em>, eliminating drift entirely at the cost of image build time.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Approach</th><th>Servers are</th><th>Drift risk</th><th>Deploy unit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>In-place (mutable)</td><td>Long-lived, modified</td><td>High</td><td>New code on old host</td></tr><tr><td>Immutable</td><td>Disposable, replaced</td><td>None</td><td>New image, new host</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Rollback mechanics by strategy</h3><p>Rollback is where these two strategies hurt most, so plan it before you deploy. With rolling, rollback means kicking off the <em>previous</em> version as a fresh rolling update - which takes as long as the original rollout and leaves a mixed-version window again. With in-place, rollback means reinstalling the prior package on every host, and if the deploy ran database migrations or rewrote config files, those may need manual reversal. The lesson is that neither offers the one-call rollback of blue-green, so both demand a rehearsed, automated rollback path and version-pinned artifacts you can redeploy on demand.</p><pre><code># Kubernetes makes rolling rollback a single command\nkubectl rollout undo deployment/web        # revert to prior revision\nkubectl rollout status deployment/web      # watch it converge\nkubectl rollout history deployment/web     # list revisions</code></pre><h3>Choosing under constraints</h3><p>The decision usually comes down to how much spare capacity you can afford and how fast you must roll back. With unlimited budget and zero tolerance for a bad release, blue-green plus canary analysis is ideal. With a huge fleet and limited headroom, rolling is the pragmatic default. When the budget is tight and a short maintenance window is acceptable, in-place wins on simplicity. A useful tiebreaker is statefulness: stateless web tiers tolerate any strategy, while stateful singletons (a primary database) often force in-place plus careful failover because you cannot simply run two of them.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A fleet of 200 stateless API nodes must be upgraded nightly with no extra budget for a duplicate environment. The team uses a rolling update with <code>maxSurge: 10%</code> and <code>maxUnavailable: 0</code>, each batch gated on a readiness probe that checks database connectivity. A bad build fails readiness on the first batch of 20, the rollout auto-pauses, and <code>kubectl rollout undo</code> restores the prior revision - all without ever degrading capacity below 100%.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Match the wording: \"update in batches with no spare environment\" = rolling; \"upgrade the existing servers, brief downtime acceptable\" = in-place. Remember that rolling and in-place both create a window where mixed or interrupted versions exist, so backward compatibility and a tested rollback path still matter. Immutable infrastructure (replace, don't modify) is the cure for the drift that in-place deployments cause.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Cloud Migration Types", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Cloud migration</span> is the movement of workloads, data, and applications between environments. CV0-004 names three directional types, and each carries distinct drivers, risks, and tooling. Knowing the direction usually tells you what the dominant constraint will be.</p><h3>On-premises-to-cloud</h3><p>The most common direction is <span class='keyterm'>on-premises-to-cloud</span>: moving workloads from owned data centers into a public cloud. Drivers include cost reduction, elasticity, exiting an aging data center, and access to managed services. The hard parts are data transfer (terabytes to petabytes), re-establishing network connectivity, and adapting applications to cloud constructs. Bulk data is often moved with offline appliances such as AWS Snowball or Azure Data Box when network transfer would take too long, and servers are lifted with tools like AWS Application Migration Service or Azure Migrate. A key planning calculation is whether to ship disks physically or stream over the wire - a full rack of data over a saturated link can take weeks, while an appliance arrives in days.</p><h3>Cloud-to-on-premises (repatriation)</h3><p>The reverse direction, <span class='keyterm'>cloud-to-on-premises</span> migration - often called <strong>repatriation</strong> - moves workloads back out of the public cloud into a private or on-prem environment. It happens when cloud costs for steady, predictable, high-volume workloads exceed the cost of owning hardware, when data-sovereignty rules tighten, or when latency to on-site equipment matters. Repatriation is harder than people expect because applications may have grown dependent on proprietary managed services (a serverless function, a managed queue) that have no on-prem equivalent, forcing re-engineering rather than a simple lift.</p><h3>Cloud-to-cloud</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>cloud-to-cloud</span> migration moves workloads between providers - for example AWS to Azure - to reduce vendor lock-in, chase pricing or feature advantages, satisfy a customer mandate, or consolidate after a merger. The central challenge is that each provider's services, IAM models, networking, and managed offerings differ, so portable workloads (containers, open-source databases, IaC written with provider-agnostic abstractions) migrate far more easily than ones wired to provider-specific services.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Migration type</th><th>Typical driver</th><th>Dominant risk</th><th>Tooling example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>On-prem to cloud</td><td>Elasticity, cost, exit data center</td><td>Data volume, connectivity</td><td>Snowball, Azure Migrate</td></tr><tr><td>Cloud to on-prem</td><td>Steady-state cost, sovereignty, latency</td><td>Managed-service dependencies</td><td>Re-platform to OSS equivalents</td></tr><tr><td>Cloud to cloud</td><td>Lock-in, pricing, M&amp;A</td><td>Provider service differences</td><td>Containers, agnostic IaC</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Resource allocation during migration</h3><p>Every migration requires deliberate <span class='keyterm'>resource allocation</span>: sizing the target compute, storage, and network so the migrated workload performs without overspending. A naive lift often over-provisions because on-prem servers were sized for peak plus growth headroom; the cloud lets you right-size to actual utilization and add elasticity instead of static headroom. Conversely, under-allocating throttles the workload after cutover. Capture baseline CPU, memory, IOPS, and throughput before migrating so the target instance type and storage tier are chosen from data rather than guesswork.</p><h3>Online vs. offline data transfer</h3><p>A pivotal early decision is <em>how</em> the data moves. <span class='keyterm'>Online transfer</span> streams data over the network (VPN, dedicated circuit, or public internet with tools like AWS DataSync, <code>azcopy</code>, or <code>rsync</code>) and suits ongoing replication and smaller volumes. <span class='keyterm'>Offline transfer</span> ships physical media - AWS Snowball, Snowmobile, or Azure Data Box - and wins when the data set is so large that streaming would take weeks or saturate the production link. The arithmetic is simple: a 100 TB data set over a 1 Gbps link, even at full utilization, takes roughly nine days; an appliance fills locally and arrives in two or three. The break-even depends on volume, link speed, and how much of that link you can spare from production.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Best for</th><th>Trade-off</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Online (DataSync, azcopy)</td><td>Smaller sets, ongoing sync</td><td>Limited by link bandwidth</td></tr><tr><td>Offline appliance (Snowball)</td><td>Tens of TB to PB, one-time</td><td>Physical shipping latency</td></tr><tr><td>Massive offline (Snowmobile)</td><td>Exabyte-scale data center exit</td><td>Logistics, security escort</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Migration phases</h3><p>A disciplined migration follows assess, plan, migrate, validate, optimize. The <em>assess</em> phase inventories dependencies and builds the business case; <em>plan</em> chooses the strategy per workload and sequences waves; <em>migrate</em> executes the move; <em>validate</em> confirms functionality and performance against the baseline; <em>optimize</em> right-sizes and tunes cost after the dust settles. Skipping assessment is the leading cause of failed migrations because hidden dependencies surface only after cutover.</p><h3>Dependency mapping and wave planning</h3><p>The single most underrated migration artifact is the <span class='keyterm'>dependency map</span>. Applications rarely run in isolation - a web tier calls an auth service, which calls a directory, which writes to a database, which feeds a reporting job. Tools that perform discovery (AWS Migration Evaluator, Azure Migrate dependency analysis) watch network flows to reveal these links automatically. From the map you sequence <span class='keyterm'>migration waves</span> so that tightly coupled systems move together, avoiding a situation where a migrated front end suffers crippling latency calling a back end still sitting on-premises. Splitting a chatty pair across the WAN seam is a classic, painful mistake.</p><h3>Cutover strategies</h3><p>The final cutover can be <strong>big bang</strong> (move everything in one window, simple but high-risk) or <strong>phased/trickle</strong> (run source and target in parallel, migrate users in groups, then decommission the source). A parallel run with bidirectional or one-way replication lets you validate the target under real load and gives a clean fallback: if the target misbehaves, traffic stays on the source. Big-bang cutovers are reserved for small systems or hard deadlines where the cost of running two environments in parallel is not justified.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>Always plan the rollback for a cutover before executing it. Keep the source system intact and reachable until the target has been validated in production for an agreed soak period - decommissioning the source too early turns any post-cutover defect into an emergency rather than a routine fallback.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A retailer's analytics platform runs continuously at high volume and its monthly cloud bill now exceeds the three-year amortized cost of owned hardware. Leadership approves repatriating the steady batch workload to a private cloud while keeping the elastic customer-facing web tier in public cloud - a deliberate cloud-to-on-premises move yielding a hybrid result.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Identify the direction first. \"Bill is too high for a constant workload, moving it back to our data center\" = cloud-to-on-premises (repatriation). \"Switching providers to avoid lock-in\" = cloud-to-cloud. Offline appliances like Snowball/Data Box appear when the data set is too large to transfer over the network in a reasonable time.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Migration Considerations and Constraints", body:"<p>Whatever the direction, a migration is evaluated against a long list of <span class='keyterm'>considerations</span> that can make or break the business case. CV0-004 enumerates these explicitly, and exam questions often hand you a constraint and ask which consideration it represents or which it should override. Treat them as a checklist.</p><h3>Technical considerations</h3><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Storage</span> - capacity, IOPS/throughput needs, and the right tier (block, file, object; hot vs. cold). Mismatched storage class is a common post-migration performance or cost surprise.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Compute</span> - matching instance families to the workload (general-purpose, compute-optimized, memory-optimized, GPU) and right-sizing against the on-prem baseline.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Networking</span> - bandwidth for the transfer itself, plus ongoing connectivity (VPN, Direct Connect/ExpressRoute), IP addressing, DNS, and latency to dependent systems.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Platform compatibility</span> - whether the OS, runtime, database, and middleware are supported on the target. Legacy or unsupported software may force a re-platform or block the move entirely.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Service availability</span> - whether the managed services the app relies on even exist in the target cloud or region; an absent equivalent forces re-architecture.</li></ul><h3>Business and operational considerations</h3><ul><li><span class='keyterm'>Cost</span> - not just compute and storage but egress data-transfer fees, licensing, and the labor of the migration itself. Total cost of ownership, not sticker price, decides.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Management overhead</span> - the ongoing operational burden. Managed services cut overhead but raise lock-in; self-managed gives control at the cost of staff time.</li><li><span class='keyterm'>Vendor lock-in</span> - dependence on proprietary services that make future exit expensive. Mitigated by open standards, containers, and abstraction layers.</li></ul><h3>Environmental considerations</h3><p>The exam explicitly lists <span class='keyterm'>environmental</span> factors, including <strong>power and cooling</strong>. On-prem, you bear the data center's power draw, cooling, and physical footprint; moving to cloud shifts that burden to the provider and can improve sustainability through higher utilization and efficient facilities. For private and hybrid builds, power and cooling capacity is a hard physical limit on how much you can deploy in a given room.</p><h3>Regulatory and compliance considerations</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Regulatory</span> and <span class='keyterm'>compliance</span> constraints frequently dominate every other factor. Data-residency laws (GDPR, regional sovereignty rules) may dictate which region or even which country a workload runs in; standards such as HIPAA, PCI DSS, and FedRAMP dictate which provider services and configurations are permissible. A workload that is cheaper and faster in one region is irrelevant if regulation forbids the data leaving its home jurisdiction.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Consideration</th><th>Key question</th><th>Failure if ignored</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Storage</td><td>Right tier and IOPS?</td><td>Slow app or runaway cost</td></tr><tr><td>Networking</td><td>Enough bandwidth + connectivity?</td><td>Stalled transfer, latency</td></tr><tr><td>Platform compatibility</td><td>Is the stack supported?</td><td>Blocked or forced re-platform</td></tr><tr><td>Cost (TCO)</td><td>Including egress + licensing?</td><td>Budget overrun</td></tr><tr><td>Vendor lock-in</td><td>Can we leave later?</td><td>Expensive future exit</td></tr><tr><td>Regulatory/compliance</td><td>Where may data live?</td><td>Legal penalties, failed audit</td></tr><tr><td>Environmental</td><td>Power, cooling, footprint?</td><td>Physical capacity limit</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>Egress (data-transfer-out) charges are a recurring blind spot. Moving data <em>into</em> a cloud is usually free, but pulling large volumes back out - or between regions - incurs per-gigabyte fees that can quietly dominate a chatty or repatriation-bound workload's bill.</p></div><h3>Quantifying total cost of ownership</h3><p>Cost decisions should rest on a <span class='keyterm'>total cost of ownership</span> (TCO) model, not a sticker-price comparison. On-prem TCO includes hardware depreciation, data-center space, power, cooling, networking, software licenses, and the staff who run it. Cloud TCO includes compute and storage charges, egress, support plans, managed-service premiums, and the labor to operate the cloud estate. A rigorous comparison also accounts for elasticity value (not paying for idle capacity) and the opportunity cost of capital tied up in owned hardware. Providers publish TCO and pricing calculators, but the credible number comes from feeding in your <em>measured</em> utilization rather than nameplate capacity.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Cost element</th><th>On-prem</th><th>Cloud</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Hardware</td><td>CapEx, depreciated</td><td>Bundled into hourly rate</td></tr><tr><td>Power and cooling</td><td>Your bill</td><td>Provider's bill</td></tr><tr><td>Data transfer out</td><td>ISP flat-ish</td><td>Per-GB egress fees</td></tr><tr><td>Scaling idle capacity</td><td>Paid for always</td><td>Scale to zero possible</td></tr><tr><td>Staff/operations</td><td>Full stack</td><td>Reduced by managed services</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Licensing and platform portability</h3><p>Software <span class='keyterm'>licensing</span> is a frequently overlooked migration constraint. Some vendor licenses are tied to physical cores or sockets and become expensive or non-compliant on multi-tenant cloud hardware; others offer <em>bring-your-own-license</em> (BYOL) or license-mobility programs. Microsoft's Azure Hybrid Benefit and Oracle's cloud licensing rules are common exam-adjacent examples of how licensing can dictate which provider, instance type, or even tenancy (dedicated host) you must choose. Always validate license portability during the assessment phase, because discovering a licensing wall after cutover can force an expensive re-platform.</p><h3>Security and identity during migration</h3><p>Migration temporarily widens the attack surface: data is in motion, credentials are duplicated across environments, and new network paths open. Encrypt data in transit (TLS, VPN) and at rest on both ends, rotate any credentials that touched the migration tooling, and federate identity early so users authenticate against one source of truth rather than divergent directories. The transition window is also when stale firewall rules and over-broad temporary permissions accumulate - schedule a cleanup pass as an explicit migration task rather than assuming temporary access will be revoked on its own.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A finance firm scopes a cloud migration and finds its core trading platform is licensed per physical core under terms that forbid multi-tenant hardware. The cheapest general-purpose instances are therefore off-limits; the team must either buy dedicated hosts (raising cost) or negotiate license mobility. Here a licensing constraint, not performance or price, dictates the entire compute design - exactly the kind of hidden consideration the assessment phase exists to surface.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>When a scenario names a regulation or data-residency rule, that constraint normally overrides cost and performance - compliance is rarely negotiable. Watch for \"environmental\" specifically meaning power and cooling, not weather. And remember vendor lock-in is the long-term cost of choosing convenient proprietary managed services.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Application Migration Strategies: The 6 R's", body:"<p>The <span class='keyterm'>6 R's</span> are the canonical taxonomy for deciding what to do with each application during a migration. CV0-004 expects you to recognize all six by definition and choose the right one from a scenario. They range from the fastest, lowest-effort move to the most transformative - and to outright not moving at all.</p><h3>Rehost (lift and shift)</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Rehost</span> moves an application to the cloud essentially unchanged - the same OS, same configuration, just running on a cloud VM instead of an on-prem server. It is the fastest path and the lowest immediate risk, ideal when speed matters (an expiring data-center lease) or when the app cannot be modified. The downside is that it captures none of the cloud's efficiency gains; a lifted VM still carries its old inefficiencies. Many teams rehost first to exit the data center, then optimize later.</p><h3>Replatform (lift and reshape)</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Replatform</span> makes a few targeted cloud optimizations without rewriting the core application - for example, moving a self-managed database onto a managed service like Amazon RDS or Azure SQL while leaving the app code mostly intact. It captures meaningful operational savings (the provider now patches and backs up the database) for modest effort, making it a popular middle ground.</p><h3>Re-architect (refactor for cloud-native)</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Re-architect</span> (sometimes called rearchitect) substantially redesigns the application to be cloud-native - decomposing a monolith into microservices, adopting serverless, or going event-driven. It is the highest-effort, highest-cost option but unlocks the most scalability, resilience, and long-term efficiency. Reserve it for strategic applications where the payoff justifies the investment.</p><h3>Refactor</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Refactor</span> restructures and optimizes existing code without changing its external behavior, often to remove technical debt or adapt the app to better use cloud features. The CompTIA list treats refactor as a distinct deep-code change; in practice it overlaps with re-architecting but emphasizes code-level improvement rather than wholesale architectural redesign.</p><h3>Retain (revisit)</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Retain</span> means deliberately <em>keeping</em> an application where it is for now - on-premises - because it is not ready, not worth migrating, or has dependencies that block a move. Retained apps are revisited in a later wave. Retaining is a legitimate decision, not a failure to act.</p><h3>Retire</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Retire</span> means decommissioning an application that is no longer needed. Migration assessments routinely discover redundant or obsolete systems; shutting them down removes cost and attack surface and is often the highest-ROI outcome of an assessment.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Effort</th><th>What changes</th><th>Choose when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Rehost</td><td>Lowest</td><td>Nothing (lift and shift)</td><td>Need speed, app can't change</td></tr><tr><td>Replatform</td><td>Low-medium</td><td>Swap a component for managed</td><td>Want quick wins, modest effort</td></tr><tr><td>Refactor</td><td>High</td><td>Internal code optimized</td><td>Pay down debt, fit cloud features</td></tr><tr><td>Re-architect</td><td>Highest</td><td>Redesign as cloud-native</td><td>Strategic app, big payoff</td></tr><tr><td>Retain</td><td>None now</td><td>Stays on-prem</td><td>Not ready or not worth moving</td></tr><tr><td>Retire</td><td>Negative (removes)</td><td>Shut down</td><td>App is obsolete/redundant</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>A seventh R: repurchase</h3><p>Many practitioners extend the list with <span class='keyterm'>repurchase</span> (sometimes \"drop and shop\"): replacing a self-hosted application entirely with a SaaS equivalent - retiring an on-prem CRM in favor of Salesforce, or self-managed email in favor of Microsoft 365. Repurchase eliminates the most operational overhead of any option because the vendor now runs everything, but it trades deep customization for a standardized product and introduces SaaS-style lock-in. While CV0-004 anchors on the six R's, recognizing repurchase helps you reason about scenarios where the best move is to stop running the software at all.</p><h3>Effort, risk, and cloud benefit trade-off</h3><p>The R's form a spectrum where increasing effort buys increasing cloud-native benefit. Rehost is fast and low-risk but captures little efficiency; re-architect and refactor are slow and risky but unlock elasticity, resilience, and the lowest long-run cost. A pragmatic portfolio strategy is to <em>rehost to meet a deadline, then refactor the workloads that matter</em> - moving up the spectrum over time rather than attempting a big-bang re-architecture of everything at once.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Time to migrate</th><th>Cloud benefit captured</th><th>Risk</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Rehost</td><td>Days to weeks</td><td>Low</td><td>Low</td></tr><tr><td>Replatform</td><td>Weeks</td><td>Medium</td><td>Low-medium</td></tr><tr><td>Repurchase</td><td>Weeks to months</td><td>High (offloaded)</td><td>Medium (lock-in)</td></tr><tr><td>Refactor</td><td>Months</td><td>High</td><td>Medium-high</td></tr><tr><td>Re-architect</td><td>Months+</td><td>Highest</td><td>High</td></tr><tr><td>Retain/Retire</td><td>None</td><td>N/A</td><td>Low</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>A worked replatform example</h3><p>Consider a Java application backed by a self-managed MySQL server on an EC2 instance. A replatform leaves the application code untouched but points it at Amazon RDS for MySQL, so the provider now handles patching, automated backups, and Multi-AZ failover. The change is a connection-string swap plus a managed database stand-up - low effort, meaningful operational payoff. The IaC for the new managed backend is compact:</p><pre><code>resource \"aws_db_instance\" \"app\" {\n  engine               = \"mysql\"\n  engine_version       = \"8.0\"\n  instance_class       = \"db.r6g.large\"\n  allocated_storage    = 200\n  multi_az             = true       # managed failover\n  backup_retention_period = 14      # managed backups\n  storage_encrypted    = true\n}</code></pre><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An assessment finds: a finance app that legally cannot change yet (retain), a duplicate reporting tool nobody uses (retire), a web app whose MySQL backend can move to RDS easily (replatform), a flagship customer portal worth rebuilding as microservices (re-architect), and an aging on-prem CRM that the business agrees to replace with a SaaS product (repurchase). One assessment, five different R's applied to one portfolio.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Map the verb: \"move unchanged / lift and shift\" = rehost; \"swap the DB for a managed service\" = replatform; \"redesign into microservices/serverless\" = re-architect; \"clean up the code\" = refactor; \"leave it on-prem for now\" = retain; \"decommission it\" = retire. Rehost is fastest and cheapest up front; re-architect is most expensive but most cloud-native.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Infrastructure as Code Foundations", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Infrastructure as Code</span> (IaC) is the practice of defining and provisioning infrastructure - networks, VMs, load balancers, databases - through machine-readable definition files instead of manual console clicks. <span class='keyterm'>Configuration as Code</span> (CaC) is the sibling practice of defining the software configuration <em>inside</em> those resources (packages, files, services). Together they turn the entire environment into versioned, reviewable, testable text, which is the backbone of repeatable cloud deployment and a heavily weighted Domain 2 topic.</p><h3>Declarative vs. imperative</h3><p>IaC tools fall into two paradigms. A <span class='keyterm'>declarative</span> tool (Terraform, CloudFormation, ARM/Bicep) describes the <em>desired end state</em> and lets the engine figure out the steps to reach it; rerunning it converges to the same state and is naturally idempotent. An <span class='keyterm'>imperative</span> approach describes the <em>sequence of steps</em> to perform. Declarative dominates infrastructure provisioning because it makes <span class='keyterm'>idempotency</span> - applying the same definition repeatedly yields the same result without duplication - the default.</p><h3>IaC vs. CaC</h3><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Infrastructure as Code</th><th>Configuration as Code</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Scope</td><td>Provisions the resources</td><td>Configures inside the resources</td></tr><tr><td>Examples</td><td>Terraform, CloudFormation, Bicep</td><td>Ansible, Puppet, Chef</td></tr><tr><td>Typical artifact</td><td>VM, VPC, load balancer, DB</td><td>Installed package, file, service state</td></tr><tr><td>Paradigm</td><td>Usually declarative</td><td>Often declarative with imperative steps</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>A declarative Terraform example</h3><p>The following HCL provisions a web server and its security group. Note there is no \"how\" - only the desired resources and their attributes. Terraform reads current state, computes the difference, and applies only what is needed.</p><pre><code>terraform {\n  required_providers {\n    aws = { source = \"hashicorp/aws\", version = \"~&gt; 5.0\" }\n  }\n}\n\nresource \"aws_instance\" \"web\" {\n  ami           = var.ami_id\n  instance_type = \"t3.medium\"\n  subnet_id     = var.subnet_id\n  tags = {\n    Name        = \"web-01\"\n    Environment = var.environment\n  }\n}\n\nresource \"aws_security_group\" \"web_sg\" {\n  name   = \"web-sg\"\n  vpc_id = var.vpc_id\n  ingress {\n    from_port   = 443\n    to_port     = 443\n    protocol    = \"tcp\"\n    cidr_blocks = [\"0.0.0.0/0\"]\n  }\n}</code></pre><h3>Why IaC matters</h3><p>The core benefits are <strong>repeatability</strong> (stand up identical dev, test, and prod environments from one definition), <strong>speed</strong> (provision in minutes, not days), <strong>consistency</strong> (no snowflake servers configured by hand), and <strong>auditability</strong> (every change is a reviewed commit). IaC also enables <span class='keyterm'>immutable infrastructure</span>: instead of patching a running server, you build a new image and replace the old instance, eliminating configuration drift entirely.</p><h3>The execution model</h3><p>A typical Terraform workflow is <code>init</code> (download providers), <code>plan</code> (preview the diff between desired and actual state), and <code>apply</code> (make the changes). The <strong>plan</strong> step is critical: it shows exactly what will be created, changed, or destroyed before anything happens, which is the safety net that makes infrastructure changes reviewable like code.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>State is central to declarative IaC. Terraform records what it manages in a <em>state file</em>; this is how it knows the difference between desired and actual. The state file must be stored remotely and locked (e.g., in an S3 bucket with DynamoDB locking) so a team does not corrupt it with concurrent runs.</p></div><h3>The IaC tool landscape</h3><p>You should recognize the major tools and which niche each fills. <span class='keyterm'>Terraform</span> (and its fork OpenTofu) is cloud-agnostic and uses HCL to provision across any provider via plugins. <span class='keyterm'>CloudFormation</span> is AWS-native (JSON/YAML); <span class='keyterm'>ARM templates</span> and the friendlier <span class='keyterm'>Bicep</span> are Azure-native; <span class='keyterm'>Google Cloud Deployment Manager</span> serves GCP. <span class='keyterm'>Pulumi</span> lets you write infrastructure in general-purpose languages (Python, TypeScript). On the CaC side, <span class='keyterm'>Ansible</span> (agentless, push, YAML), <span class='keyterm'>Puppet</span> and <span class='keyterm'>Chef</span> (agent-based, pull) dominate configuration management.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Scope</th><th>Language</th><th>Cloud</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Terraform / OpenTofu</td><td>Provisioning</td><td>HCL</td><td>Agnostic</td></tr><tr><td>CloudFormation</td><td>Provisioning</td><td>JSON/YAML</td><td>AWS</td></tr><tr><td>ARM / Bicep</td><td>Provisioning</td><td>JSON / Bicep DSL</td><td>Azure</td></tr><tr><td>Pulumi</td><td>Provisioning</td><td>Python/TS/Go</td><td>Agnostic</td></tr><tr><td>Ansible</td><td>Configuration</td><td>YAML</td><td>Agnostic</td></tr><tr><td>Puppet / Chef</td><td>Configuration</td><td>DSL / Ruby</td><td>Agnostic</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Push vs. pull configuration models</h3><p>CaC tools split on how the desired state reaches the node. In a <span class='keyterm'>push</span> model (Ansible), a control node connects out over SSH/WinRM and applies the configuration on demand - simple, agentless, but the control node must reach every target. In a <span class='keyterm'>pull</span> model (Puppet, Chef), each managed node runs an agent that periodically fetches its catalog from a central server and self-converges - scales to thousands of nodes and continuously corrects drift, at the cost of running an agent and master infrastructure. The pull model's periodic convergence is itself a form of continuous drift remediation.</p><h3>A CloudFormation comparison</h3><p>To see the same declarative idea in a provider-native format, here is a minimal CloudFormation template that provisions an encrypted bucket - functionally similar intent to the Terraform above, expressed in AWS's own JSON/YAML dialect with intrinsic functions and parameters:</p><pre><code>Parameters:\n  EnvName: { Type: String, Default: prod }\nResources:\n  AppBucket:\n    Type: AWS::S3::Bucket\n    Properties:\n      BucketName: !Sub \"acme-${EnvName}-data\"\n      BucketEncryption:\n        ServerSideEncryptionConfiguration:\n          - ServerSideEncryptionByDefault:\n              SSEAlgorithm: aws:kms</code></pre><h3>GitOps and the deployment pipeline</h3><p>IaC reaches its full potential inside a <span class='keyterm'>GitOps</span> pipeline, where the Git repository is the single source of truth and an automated agent reconciles the live environment to match the committed definitions. A merge to the main branch triggers <code>plan</code> then <code>apply</code> (or a tool like Argo CD/Flux continuously syncs Kubernetes manifests). This makes every infrastructure change a reviewed, attributable, revertible pull request - the same rigor applied to application code, now applied to the environment itself.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>IaC provisions the infrastructure; CaC configures what runs inside it. Declarative (desired state, idempotent) is the norm for provisioning. If a question stresses \"apply it again and again with the same result,\" the property is idempotency. Immutable infrastructure means replace rather than modify.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"IaC Scripting Logic: Variables, Types, Operators", body:"<p>IaC and CaC are real programming, and CV0-004 expects familiarity with the <span class='keyterm'>scripting logic</span> they share: variables, data types, operators, conditionals, and functions. You will not write production code on the exam, but you must read a snippet and predict its effect. This section walks the building blocks using Terraform HCL and a touch of shell.</p><h3>Variables</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>variable</span> is a named placeholder that parameterizes a definition so the same code serves many environments. Inputs are declared with types and optional defaults, then referenced as <code>var.name</code>. This is what makes one module reusable across dev, staging, and prod.</p><pre><code>variable \"instance_count\" {\n  type    = number\n  default = 2\n}\nvariable \"environment\" {\n  type    = string\n  default = \"dev\"\n}\nvariable \"enable_backups\" {\n  type    = bool\n  default = true\n}</code></pre><h3>Data types</h3><p>Common <span class='keyterm'>data types</span> are <strong>string</strong> (text), <strong>number</strong> (integer or float), <strong>boolean</strong> (true/false), <strong>list/array</strong> (ordered collection), and <strong>map/object</strong> (key-value pairs). Choosing the right type matters because operators and functions behave differently per type - you cannot do arithmetic on a string, and a map is indexed by key rather than position.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Example value</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>String</td><td>\"us-east-1\"</td><td>Names, regions, AMI ids</td></tr><tr><td>Number</td><td>3</td><td>Counts, sizes, ports</td></tr><tr><td>Boolean</td><td>true</td><td>Feature toggles</td></tr><tr><td>List/array</td><td>[\"a\",\"b\",\"c\"]</td><td>Subnet ids, AZ lists</td></tr><tr><td>Map/object</td><td>{ env = \"prod\" }</td><td>Tags, structured config</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Operators</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Operators</span> combine values. <strong>Arithmetic</strong> operators (<code>+ - * / %</code>) compute numbers; <strong>comparison</strong> operators (<code>== != &gt; &lt; &gt;= &lt;=</code>) produce booleans; <strong>logical</strong> operators (<code>&amp;&amp;</code> and, <code>||</code> or, <code>!</code> not) combine booleans. These drive the conditionals that make IaC adapt to its inputs - for example, comparing <code>var.environment == \"prod\"</code> to decide whether to enable a costly redundant tier.</p><h3>Functions</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>function</span> takes inputs and returns a value, encapsulating reusable logic. IaC languages ship built-in functions for strings, collections, and math. Below, <code>length()</code> counts a list and <code>upper()</code> transforms a string; the <code>local</code> block names a derived value computed once and reused.</p><pre><code>locals {\n  az_count   = length(var.availability_zones)\n  name_upper = upper(var.environment)\n  is_prod    = var.environment == \"prod\"\n}</code></pre><h3>Putting it together in shell</h3><p>The same primitives appear in CaC and glue scripts. This Bash fragment uses a variable, a comparison operator, an arithmetic operator, and a function-like structure:</p><pre><code>#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\nENV=\"${1:-dev}\"               # variable with default\ncount=$(( 2 * 3 ))            # arithmetic operator\nif [[ \"$ENV\" == \"prod\" ]]; then   # comparison + conditional\n  replicas=6\nelse\n  replicas=2\nfi\necho \"Deploying $replicas replicas to $ENV\"</code></pre><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>You may be shown a snippet and asked what it does. Track the variable's value, apply the operator, and follow the conditional. Know the three operator families: arithmetic (math), comparison (yields true/false), logical (combines booleans). A boolean variable is almost always a feature toggle.</p></div><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>Strong typing catches errors early: declaring <code>instance_count</code> as <code>number</code> means passing <code>\"two\"</code> fails at validation rather than producing undefined behavior at apply time. Treat type declarations as the first line of testing.</p></div><h3>Variable precedence and where values come from</h3><p>A real deployment supplies variable values from several sources, and they follow a defined <span class='keyterm'>precedence</span> order so the most specific wins. In Terraform, the order from lowest to highest is: defaults in the declaration, environment variables (<code>TF_VAR_name</code>), <code>terraform.tfvars</code> files, then <code>-var</code> flags on the command line. Understanding precedence prevents the frustrating bug where a value you set in one place is silently overridden by another. The same layering idea appears in Ansible (role defaults, inventory vars, playbook vars, extra-vars) and in CI systems that inject secrets as environment variables.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Source</th><th>Precedence</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Declaration default</td><td>Lowest</td><td>Sensible fallback</td></tr><tr><td>Environment (TF_VAR_)</td><td>Low</td><td>CI-injected secrets</td></tr><tr><td>tfvars file</td><td>Medium</td><td>Per-environment config</td></tr><tr><td>-var CLI flag</td><td>Highest</td><td>One-off override</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Validation and constraints</h3><p>Beyond a bare type, modern IaC lets you attach <span class='keyterm'>validation</span> rules so bad input is rejected before any resource is touched. This is logic operating on the variable itself - a conditional that must evaluate true or the run aborts with a clear message. It is far cheaper to fail here than to discover an invalid region halfway through an apply.</p><pre><code>variable \"environment\" {\n  type    = string\n  default = \"dev\"\n  validation {\n    condition     = contains([\"dev\", \"staging\", \"prod\"], var.environment)\n    error_message = \"environment must be dev, staging, or prod.\"\n  }\n}</code></pre><h3>Complex and nested data types</h3><p>Production IaC rarely uses bare scalars; it composes <span class='keyterm'>complex types</span> - lists of objects, maps of maps - to describe whole fleets compactly. A single map of objects can define every environment's sizing in one readable block that downstream resources iterate over, keeping related settings together rather than scattered across dozens of variables.</p><pre><code>variable \"env_config\" {\n  type = map(object({\n    instance_type = string\n    min_size      = number\n    multi_az      = bool\n  }))\n  default = {\n    dev  = { instance_type = \"t3.small\",  min_size = 1, multi_az = false }\n    prod = { instance_type = \"m5.xlarge\", min_size = 3, multi_az = true  }\n  }\n}</code></pre><h3>Type coercion and string interpolation</h3><p>Be aware of <span class='keyterm'>type coercion</span>: many languages will quietly convert between types, and string <span class='keyterm'>interpolation</span> embeds a variable inside text, as in <code>\"web-${var.environment}-01\"</code>. Coercion is convenient but a source of subtle bugs - a number coerced to a string compares differently than you expect. The defensive habit is to declare the type you intend and let validation reject anything that does not fit, rather than relying on the engine's implicit conversions.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An engineer runs an apply that ignores the <code>instance_type</code> they carefully set in <code>prod.tfvars</code>, because a leftover <code>TF_VAR_instance_type=t3.micro</code> in their shell sat at a different precedence than expected - and a stray <code>-var</code> flag in the CI job overrode both. The fix is knowing the precedence chain: CLI <code>-var</code> beats tfvars beats environment beats defaults.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"IaC Logic: Conditionals, Loops, and Functions", body:"<p>Beyond simple variables, IaC uses <span class='keyterm'>conditionals</span> and iteration to make one definition adapt to its inputs and to avoid copy-pasting near-identical resources. CV0-004 lists conditionals and functions explicitly under scripting logic, so you must read these constructs comfortably.</p><h3>Conditional expressions</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>conditional</span> chooses between values based on a boolean test. Terraform's ternary form is <code>condition ? value_if_true : value_if_false</code>. Here the instance type and backup retention scale up only in production, so a single module produces a cheap dev environment and a robust prod one from the same code:</p><pre><code>resource \"aws_instance\" \"app\" {\n  ami           = var.ami_id\n  instance_type = var.environment == \"prod\" ? \"m5.xlarge\" : \"t3.small\"\n}\n\nresource \"aws_db_instance\" \"db\" {\n  allocated_storage       = var.environment == \"prod\" ? 500 : 20\n  backup_retention_period = var.environment == \"prod\" ? 30 : 1\n  multi_az                = var.environment == \"prod\"\n}</code></pre><h3>Iteration with count and for_each</h3><p>To create many similar resources without repetition, declarative tools provide <span class='keyterm'>iteration</span>. Terraform's <code>count</code> creates N copies indexed by number; <code>for_each</code> creates one resource per element of a map or set, which is safer when the collection changes because resources are keyed by name rather than position.</p><pre><code># count: three identical subnets across AZs\nresource \"aws_subnet\" \"app\" {\n  count             = length(var.availability_zones)\n  vpc_id            = var.vpc_id\n  availability_zone = var.availability_zones[count.index]\n  cidr_block        = cidrsubnet(var.vpc_cidr, 8, count.index)\n}\n\n# for_each: one bucket per named environment\nresource \"aws_s3_bucket\" \"env\" {\n  for_each = toset([\"dev\", \"staging\", \"prod\"])\n  bucket   = \"acme-app-${each.key}\"\n}</code></pre><h3>Functions that transform data</h3><p>Built-in <span class='keyterm'>functions</span> reshape values so they fit a resource's expected input. <code>cidrsubnet()</code> carves a subnet from a larger block, <code>merge()</code> combines maps (handy for layering default tags with per-resource tags), and <code>lookup()</code> reads a map with a fallback. Functions keep logic declarative while still computing derived values.</p><pre><code>locals {\n  common_tags = { Owner = \"platform\", ManagedBy = \"terraform\" }\n  app_tags    = merge(local.common_tags, { Service = \"checkout\" })\n  size        = lookup(var.size_map, var.environment, \"t3.micro\")\n}</code></pre><table><thead><tr><th>Construct</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Example keyword</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Conditional</td><td>Pick a value by test</td><td><code>cond ? a : b</code></td></tr><tr><td>Count loop</td><td>N copies by index</td><td><code>count</code></td></tr><tr><td>Map loop</td><td>One per named item</td><td><code>for_each</code></td></tr><tr><td>Function</td><td>Transform/derive a value</td><td><code>merge()</code>, <code>length()</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Conditional resource creation</h3><p>A powerful idiom combines <code>count</code> with a boolean to create a resource <em>only when needed</em> - the cloud equivalent of an <code>if</code> statement around a whole block. Setting <code>count = var.enable_monitoring ? 1 : 0</code> means the resource exists when the flag is true and vanishes when false. This is how one module conditionally provisions an expensive monitoring stack in prod but skips it in dev, all from a single definition.</p><pre><code># Create the alarm only when monitoring is enabled\nresource \"aws_cloudwatch_metric_alarm\" \"cpu\" {\n  count               = var.enable_monitoring ? 1 : 0\n  alarm_name          = \"high-cpu-${var.environment}\"\n  comparison_operator = \"GreaterThanThreshold\"\n  threshold           = 80\n  metric_name         = \"CPUUtilization\"\n  namespace           = \"AWS/EC2\"\n}</code></pre><h3>Dynamic blocks for repeated nested config</h3><p>When a resource needs a variable number of <em>nested</em> blocks - say, several ingress rules in one security group - a <span class='keyterm'>dynamic block</span> iterates to generate them. This avoids hand-writing each rule and lets the rule set come from a variable, so adding a port is a one-line data change rather than a code edit.</p><pre><code>resource \"aws_security_group\" \"web\" {\n  name = \"web-${var.environment}\"\n  dynamic \"ingress\" {\n    for_each = var.allowed_ports          # e.g. [80, 443]\n    content {\n      from_port   = ingress.value\n      to_port     = ingress.value\n      protocol    = \"tcp\"\n      cidr_blocks = [\"0.0.0.0/0\"]\n    }\n  }\n}</code></pre><h3>Loops in configuration as code</h3><p>The same iteration logic appears in CaC. An Ansible <code>loop</code> applies a task once per list item - installing a set of packages, creating several users - without duplicating the task. This Ansible snippet installs three packages from a single task using the loop construct:</p><pre><code>- name: Install required packages\n  ansible.builtin.package:\n    name: \"{{ item }}\"\n    state: present\n  loop:\n    - nginx\n    - git\n    - htop</code></pre><h3>Categories of built-in functions</h3><p>It helps to group the functions you will encounter. <strong>String</strong> functions (<code>upper</code>, <code>lower</code>, <code>replace</code>, <code>format</code>, <code>join</code>, <code>split</code>) reshape text; <strong>collection</strong> functions (<code>length</code>, <code>merge</code>, <code>concat</code>, <code>keys</code>, <code>values</code>, <code>contains</code>) operate on lists and maps; <strong>numeric</strong> functions (<code>min</code>, <code>max</code>, <code>ceil</code>, <code>floor</code>) handle math; and <strong>encoding/filesystem</strong> functions (<code>jsonencode</code>, <code>file</code>, <code>templatefile</code>) bridge to other formats and files. Recognizing which category a function belongs to tells you what type it expects and returns.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Examples</th><th>Returns</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>String</td><td>upper, join, format</td><td>String</td></tr><tr><td>Collection</td><td>length, merge, contains</td><td>Number/map/bool</td></tr><tr><td>Numeric</td><td>min, max, ceil</td><td>Number</td></tr><tr><td>Encoding</td><td>jsonencode, templatefile</td><td>String</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why this avoids drift and duplication</h3><p>Iteration and conditionals replace dozens of hand-written, slightly different resource blocks with one parameterized definition. That single source of truth is what keeps fifty subnets genuinely identical and what lets a prod-vs-dev difference live in one readable expression rather than two divergent copies that drift apart over time. The deeper payoff is reviewability: a reviewer reads one loop and one conditional instead of auditing fifty near-identical blocks for the one that someone edited by hand.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Recognize the ternary <code>?:</code> as a conditional and <code>count</code>/<code>for_each</code> as loops. <code>for_each</code> is generally preferred over <code>count</code> because removing a middle element with <code>count</code> renumbers and can destroy/recreate the wrong resources, while <code>for_each</code> keys by name.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"IaC Formats: JSON and YAML", body:"<p>IaC and CaC definitions are written in structured text, and CV0-004 calls out two formats by name: <span class='keyterm'>JSON</span> and <span class='keyterm'>YAML</span>. They represent the same kinds of data - scalars, lists, and maps - but differ sharply in readability and where each is conventionally used. You should be able to read both and recognize the same structure expressed in either.</p><h3>JSON</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>JSON</span> (JavaScript Object Notation) uses braces for objects, brackets for arrays, and quoted keys. It is strict, unambiguous, and machine-friendly, which is why APIs and tools such as AWS CloudFormation (which also accepts YAML) and many policy documents use it. Its drawbacks are verbosity and intolerance of comments and trailing commas.</p><pre><code>{\n  \"Resources\": {\n    \"WebBucket\": {\n      \"Type\": \"AWS::S3::Bucket\",\n      \"Properties\": {\n        \"BucketName\": \"acme-web-assets\",\n        \"VersioningConfiguration\": { \"Status\": \"Enabled\" },\n        \"Tags\": [\n          { \"Key\": \"Environment\", \"Value\": \"prod\" }\n        ]\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}</code></pre><h3>YAML</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>YAML</span> (YAML Ain't Markup Language) uses indentation instead of braces, allows comments, and is far less noisy, which makes it the default for human-edited configuration - Kubernetes manifests, Ansible playbooks, CI/CD pipelines, and Docker Compose. The same S3 bucket as above is dramatically shorter in YAML:</p><pre><code>Resources:\n  WebBucket:\n    Type: AWS::S3::Bucket\n    Properties:\n      BucketName: acme-web-assets\n      VersioningConfiguration:\n        Status: Enabled\n      Tags:\n        - Key: Environment        # comments are allowed\n          Value: prod</code></pre><h3>Configuration as Code in YAML</h3><p>CaC tools lean on YAML. This Ansible playbook installs and starts a web server - a declarative description of desired software state, the configuration counterpart to the infrastructure IaC defined earlier:</p><pre><code>- name: Configure web tier\n  hosts: webservers\n  become: true\n  vars:\n    pkg: nginx\n  tasks:\n    - name: Install package\n      ansible.builtin.package:\n        name: \"{{ pkg }}\"\n        state: present\n    - name: Ensure service running and enabled\n      ansible.builtin.service:\n        name: \"{{ pkg }}\"\n        state: started\n        enabled: true</code></pre><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>JSON</th><th>YAML</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Syntax</td><td>Braces, brackets, quotes</td><td>Indentation, minimal punctuation</td></tr><tr><td>Comments</td><td>Not supported</td><td>Supported (#)</td></tr><tr><td>Readability</td><td>Verbose</td><td>Concise, human-friendly</td></tr><tr><td>Common use</td><td>APIs, policies, CloudFormation</td><td>K8s, Ansible, CI/CD, Compose</td></tr><tr><td>Whitespace sensitivity</td><td>Insensitive</td><td>Strict - indentation is meaning</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The shared data model</h3><p>The reason tools convert freely between JSON and YAML is that both serialize the same three primitives: <strong>scalars</strong> (a single string, number, or boolean), <strong>sequences</strong> (ordered lists), and <strong>mappings</strong> (unordered key-value pairs). YAML is in fact a superset of JSON - any valid JSON is also valid YAML - which is why a tool can ingest either and emit either. Internally both become the same tree of maps, lists, and scalars that the IaC engine walks.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Data concept</th><th>JSON syntax</th><th>YAML syntax</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Mapping</td><td>{ \"k\": \"v\" }</td><td>k: v</td></tr><tr><td>Sequence</td><td>[ 1, 2, 3 ]</td><td>- 1 (one per line)</td></tr><tr><td>Nested map</td><td>{ \"a\": { \"b\": 1 } }</td><td>a:\\n  b: 1 (indented)</td></tr><tr><td>String scalar</td><td>\"text\"</td><td>text (quotes optional)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>YAML features JSON lacks</h3><p>YAML adds conveniences that explain its popularity for human-authored config. <span class='keyterm'>Anchors and aliases</span> (<code>&amp;name</code> to define, <code>*name</code> to reference) let you define a block once and reuse it, reducing duplication. Multi-line scalars use <code>|</code> (literal, preserves newlines) or <code>&gt;</code> (folded, joins lines) - handy for embedding a script or certificate. Documents can be separated with <code>---</code> so several manifests live in one file. None of these exist in JSON, which is why JSON stays the machine-to-machine format while YAML wins for files people edit.</p><pre><code># Anchor and alias reuse a common block\ndefaults: &amp;defaults\n  retries: 3\n  timeout: 30\nstaging:\n  &lt;&lt;: *defaults\n  host: staging.example.com\nproduction:\n  &lt;&lt;: *defaults\n  host: prod.example.com</code></pre><h3>JSON for policy and machine interchange</h3><p>JSON dominates where a machine produces or consumes the document and ambiguity is unacceptable - API request and response bodies, IAM policy documents, and tool state files. Its strictness is a feature there: no comments to drift out of date, no whitespace ambiguity, no surprise type coercion. An IAM policy is a canonical example of JSON used as declarative configuration:</p><pre><code>{\n  \"Version\": \"2012-10-17\",\n  \"Statement\": [\n    {\n      \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\n      \"Action\": [\"s3:GetObject\"],\n      \"Resource\": \"arn:aws:s3:::acme-web-assets/*\"\n    }\n  ]\n}</code></pre><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>YAML's biggest footgun is indentation: a single misaligned space changes structure or breaks the parse, and tabs are forbidden. A second classic trap is the \"Norway problem\" - unquoted <code>no</code>, <code>yes</code>, <code>on</code>, <code>off</code>, and <code>NO</code> (Norway's country code) are interpreted as booleans unless quoted. JSON trades these risks for verbosity. Many tools accept both and convert between them, since they map to the same underlying data model.</p></div><h3>Schema validation and linting</h3><p>Because both formats are easy to mistype, production pipelines validate them against a <span class='keyterm'>schema</span> and run a linter before use. JSON Schema can assert that required keys exist and values have the right type; <code>yamllint</code> and format-aware validators (<code>kubeval</code> for Kubernetes, <code>cfn-lint</code> for CloudFormation) catch structural errors and policy violations before a deploy. This is the format-level counterpart to the IaC testing discussed elsewhere: catch the typo at commit time, not at apply time when a malformed manifest has already half-deployed.</p><pre><code># Lint and validate before applying\nyamllint deployment.yaml\nkubeval deployment.yaml          # validate against k8s schema\ncfn-lint template.yaml           # validate CloudFormation</code></pre><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A platform engineer pastes a Kubernetes manifest where one nested field is indented with a tab instead of spaces. The cluster rejects it with an opaque parse error at deploy time, stalling a release. After adding <code>yamllint</code> as a pre-commit hook, the same mistake is now caught locally in milliseconds with a precise line number - illustrating why whitespace-sensitive YAML demands automated linting in any serious pipeline.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Both formats express maps (key-value), lists, and scalars. If a snippet uses braces and quoted keys, it is JSON; if it uses indentation and dashes for list items, it is YAML. Remember YAML allows comments and is whitespace-sensitive and a superset of JSON; JSON is strict, comment-free, and favored for APIs, policies, and machine interchange. When a question shows a config file with comments, it must be YAML, since JSON cannot hold them.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"IaC Practices: Repeatability, Versioning, Documentation", body:"<p>Writing IaC is only half the discipline; CV0-004 lists a set of <span class='keyterm'>practices</span> that make it trustworthy in production: repeatability, versioning, testing, drift detection, and documentation. This section covers repeatability, versioning, and documentation; the next covers drift detection and testing in depth.</p><h3>Repeatability</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Repeatability</span> is the property that running the same definition produces the same environment every time, anywhere. It rests on <span class='keyterm'>idempotency</span> - applying a definition that is already satisfied changes nothing - and on parameterization through variables so one module can build dev, test, and prod identically except for the inputs you intend to differ. Repeatability is what kills \"works on my machine\" infrastructure: the environment is reconstructed from code, not from an undocumented sequence of console clicks.</p><h3>Versioning</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Versioning</span> stores IaC in a version-control system (Git) so every change is a reviewable, attributable, revertible commit. This gives you a full history of who changed the infrastructure and why, the ability to roll back to any prior known-good state, and the foundation for code review and CI/CD. Modules and providers are themselves version-pinned so a build is reproducible months later.</p><pre><code># Pin provider and module versions for reproducible builds\nterraform {\n  required_version = \"&gt;= 1.6.0\"\n  required_providers {\n    aws = { source = \"hashicorp/aws\", version = \"~&gt; 5.40\" }\n  }\n}\n\nmodule \"network\" {\n  source  = \"app.terraform.io/acme/network/aws\"\n  version = \"3.2.1\"   # exact pin, not \"latest\"\n}</code></pre><p>Pinning matters: an unpinned <code>latest</code> means a build that worked yesterday can break today when an upstream module changes. Treat infrastructure dependencies with the same rigor as application dependencies.</p><h3>Branching and review flow</h3><p>Mature teams gate infrastructure changes through pull requests, with an automated <code>terraform plan</code> posted to the PR so reviewers see exactly what will change before approval. Merging to the main branch triggers the <code>apply</code>. This is GitOps in spirit: the repository is the single source of truth, and the live environment is reconciled to match it.</p><h3>Modules and the DRY principle</h3><p>Repeatability scales through <span class='keyterm'>modules</span> - reusable, versioned packages of IaC that encapsulate a pattern (a standard VPC, a hardened bucket, a three-tier app) behind a small set of inputs and outputs. A module is the infrastructure equivalent of a function: write the network design once, then call it for every environment with different parameters. This embodies the <span class='keyterm'>DRY</span> (don't repeat yourself) principle - one definition, many instantiations - so a fix to the module propagates everywhere it is used rather than needing the same edit in a dozen copies.</p><pre><code># One module, called per environment with different inputs\nmodule \"network_dev\" {\n  source     = \"./modules/network\"\n  cidr_block = \"10.10.0.0/16\"\n  az_count   = 2\n}\nmodule \"network_prod\" {\n  source     = \"./modules/network\"\n  cidr_block = \"10.20.0.0/16\"\n  az_count   = 3\n}</code></pre><h3>Environment isolation strategies</h3><p>A recurring design question is how to keep dev, staging, and prod separate while sharing code. Two common patterns are <strong>workspaces</strong> (one codebase, switchable state per environment) and <strong>directory-per-environment</strong> (separate state and tfvars files under <code>env/dev</code>, <code>env/prod</code>). The directory approach is generally preferred for production because it isolates state files completely, so a mistake in dev cannot touch prod's state, and each environment can pin different module versions during a phased rollout.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Pattern</th><th>State isolation</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Workspaces</td><td>Same backend, separate state keys</td><td>Quick, similar environments</td></tr><tr><td>Directory per env</td><td>Fully separate state + config</td><td>Strong prod isolation</td></tr><tr><td>Separate accounts</td><td>Separate cloud accounts entirely</td><td>Strict blast-radius control</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Semantic versioning of modules</h3><p>Shared modules should follow <span class='keyterm'>semantic versioning</span> (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH) so consumers understand the risk of an upgrade. A PATCH bump is a safe backward-compatible fix, MINOR adds backward-compatible features, and MAJOR signals a breaking change that requires consumer edits. Pinning to <code>~&gt; 3.2</code> accepts patches and minors but not a breaking 4.x, giving you safe automatic improvements without surprise breakage - the same dependency discipline used for application libraries.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Practice</th><th>What it delivers</th><th>Mechanism</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Repeatability</td><td>Identical environments on demand</td><td>Idempotency + variables</td></tr><tr><td>Versioning</td><td>History, rollback, attribution</td><td>Git, version pins</td></tr><tr><td>Documentation</td><td>Understandable, maintainable code</td><td>Comments, READMEs, self-describing names</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Documentation</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Documentation</span> keeps IaC maintainable as it grows. Good practice includes descriptive resource and variable names, inline comments explaining non-obvious choices, variable <code>description</code> fields, and a module README stating inputs, outputs, and usage. Crucially, well-written declarative code is partly self-documenting - the definition <em>is</em> the spec of what exists - but it never excuses omitting the <em>why</em>. Auto-generation tools (such as terraform-docs) can produce input/output tables straight from the code so docs do not drift from reality.</p><pre><code>variable \"retention_days\" {\n  type        = number\n  default     = 30\n  description = \"Backup retention. Prod requires &gt;= 30 per compliance policy CP-09.\"\n}</code></pre><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A team must stand up an identical disaster-recovery environment in a second region. Because their entire production stack is captured as a versioned, parameterized Terraform module, they call the same module with the DR region and CIDR as inputs and apply it - reproducing production faithfully in under an hour. Without IaC this would be a multi-day, error-prone manual rebuild that almost certainly diverges from production in subtle ways.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Versioning IaC in Git is what enables rollback and audit of infrastructure changes - the same benefits version control gives application code. Repeatability depends on idempotency and parameterization through modules. If a question asks how to guarantee dev and prod are identical, the answer is the same parameterized IaC applied to both with only the intended inputs differing. Pin module and provider versions (semantic versioning) so a build is reproducible months later.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"IaC Practices: Drift Detection and Testing", body:"<p>Two of the most exam-relevant IaC practices are <span class='keyterm'>drift detection</span> and <span class='keyterm'>testing</span>. They are how teams keep reality matching the code and how they catch mistakes before they reach production.</p><h3>Configuration drift</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Drift</span> is the divergence between the actual state of infrastructure and the state declared in code. It happens when someone makes a manual change in the console (a \"hotfix\" firewall rule, a hand-resized disk), or when an external process modifies a resource. Drift is dangerous because it silently undoes the guarantees of IaC: the code no longer describes reality, so a future apply may revert a critical manual fix, or a disaster-recovery rebuild from code produces a subtly different environment.</p><h3>Detecting drift</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Drift detection</span> compares declared state to actual state and reports the differences. In Terraform this is what <code>plan</code> reveals: if it shows changes when you have not edited the code, something drifted. Tools and platforms (AWS CloudFormation drift detection, Terraform Cloud, Driftctl) can run this continuously and alert. The remediation is to either codify the manual change (bring it into the definition) or re-apply to overwrite the drift back to the declared state.</p><pre><code># Detect drift: a plan with no code changes should be empty\nterraform plan -detailed-exitcode\n# exit 0 = no changes (no drift)\n# exit 2 = drift detected (changes present)\n# exit 1 = error</code></pre><p>The <code>-detailed-exitcode</code> flag is what makes drift detection automatable: a CI job runs the plan nightly and alerts the team when the exit code is 2.</p><h3>Testing IaC</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Testing</span> validates IaC before it provisions anything. It spans several layers, from cheap static checks to full deploy-and-verify:</p><ul><li><strong>Linting / formatting</strong> - <code>terraform fmt</code> and <code>terraform validate</code> catch syntax and basic schema errors instantly.</li><li><strong>Static analysis / policy</strong> - tools like tflint, Checkov, or Sentinel/OPA enforce rules (no public S3 buckets, mandatory tags, encryption required) before apply.</li><li><strong>Plan review</strong> - reading the <code>plan</code> diff is itself a test of intent.</li><li><strong>Integration testing</strong> - frameworks like Terratest deploy into an ephemeral environment, assert the resources behave, and tear them down.</li></ul><pre><code># A pipeline gate: format, validate, then policy scan\nterraform fmt -check\nterraform validate\ncheckov -d . --quiet     # fails build on policy violations</code></pre><table><thead><tr><th>Test layer</th><th>Catches</th><th>Cost/speed</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>fmt / validate</td><td>Syntax, schema errors</td><td>Instant, free</td></tr><tr><td>Policy scan</td><td>Insecure or non-compliant config</td><td>Fast, pre-apply</td></tr><tr><td>Plan review</td><td>Unintended changes</td><td>Fast, manual</td></tr><tr><td>Integration</td><td>Real runtime behavior</td><td>Slow, deploys resources</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Causes and prevention of drift</h3><p>Drift has predictable causes: emergency console changes during incidents, manual fixes that never get codified, automated processes (auto-scaling, auto-healing) that legitimately alter resources, and changes made by other teams sharing an account. The strongest prevention is organizational, not technical - restricting write access so humans <em>cannot</em> change production by hand, forcing all changes through the pipeline. Where automated systems must mutate resources, those attributes are excluded from drift comparison (Terraform's <code>ignore_changes</code> lifecycle rule) so the tool does not fight the autoscaler.</p><pre><code>resource \"aws_autoscaling_group\" \"web\" {\n  desired_capacity = 3\n  lifecycle {\n    ignore_changes = [desired_capacity]   # autoscaler owns this; not drift\n  }\n}</code></pre><h3>Remediating drift</h3><p>When drift is detected you have three responses. <strong>Revert</strong>: re-apply the code to overwrite the manual change, appropriate when the change was unwanted. <strong>Absorb</strong>: update the code to match reality and commit it, appropriate when the manual change was a good fix that should become permanent. <strong>Import</strong>: bring an unmanaged resource under IaC control with <code>terraform import</code> so future changes flow through code. Choosing the right response per case is the day-to-day craft of running IaC at scale.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Situation</th><th>Response</th><th>Command/action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Unwanted manual change</td><td>Revert</td><td>terraform apply</td></tr><tr><td>Good manual change</td><td>Absorb into code</td><td>Edit code, commit, apply</td></tr><tr><td>Resource created outside IaC</td><td>Import</td><td>terraform import</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The testing pyramid for IaC</h3><p>IaC testing mirrors the classic testing pyramid: many cheap, fast checks at the base and few expensive, slow ones at the top. At the base sit formatting and validation; above them, unit-style policy checks on the plan; then contract/integration tests that deploy to throwaway environments; and at the apex, end-to-end tests against a full staging stack. Spending your effort proportionally - lots of fast checks, a handful of slow ones - keeps the pipeline both safe and fast.</p><h3>Policy as code in depth</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Policy as code</span> deserves emphasis because it shifts compliance left, catching violations before resources exist. Frameworks like Open Policy Agent (Rego), HashiCorp Sentinel, and Checkov evaluate the planned changes against organizational rules - encryption mandatory, no <code>0.0.0.0/0</code> on sensitive ports, required tags present - and fail the build on a violation. This turns audit findings into pre-merge errors, which is dramatically cheaper than remediating non-compliant infrastructure already in production.</p><pre><code># OPA/Rego policy: deny unencrypted S3 buckets\ndeny[msg] {\n  bucket := input.resource.aws_s3_bucket[name]\n  not bucket.server_side_encryption_configuration\n  msg := sprintf(\"bucket %v must enable encryption\", [name])\n}</code></pre><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An engineer widens a security group in the console to debug an outage and forgets to revert it. A nightly <code>terraform plan -detailed-exitcode</code> returns exit code 2, alerting the platform team to drift. They review the change, decide it is unwanted, and re-apply the code to restore the locked-down rule - closing the gap automatically rather than discovering it during the next breach.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A developer opens a pull request that adds an S3 bucket without encryption. Before any human reviews it, the CI pipeline runs Checkov, the policy scan fails with \"bucket must enable encryption,\" and the merge is blocked. The developer adds the encryption block and the build passes. The insecure config never reached production - policy as code caught it at the cheapest possible point.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Drift = actual infrastructure no longer matches the code, usually from manual changes. Detect it by running <code>plan</code> and seeing unexpected diffs; remediate by re-applying or codifying the change. Testing IaC ranges from fmt/validate (syntax) to policy scanning (compliance) to integration tests (real behavior) - know that policy-as-code can block insecure config before it deploys.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Provisioning to Requirements: Compute, Storage, Network", body:"<p>Provisioning is not just \"spin up a server\" - it is choosing resources that satisfy explicit <span class='keyterm'>requirements</span>. CV0-004 lists eight requirement dimensions, and each one steers concrete choices about instance type, storage tier, region, and redundancy. This section covers the three infrastructure pillars: compute, storage, and network; the next covers the cross-cutting business and quality requirements.</p><h3>Compute requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Compute requirements</span> dictate the instance family and size. Cloud providers group instances by profile, and matching the workload to the family is the single biggest lever on both performance and cost:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Workload profile</th><th>Family (AWS example)</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Balanced web/app</td><td>General-purpose (M, T)</td><td>Even CPU-to-memory ratio</td></tr><tr><td>CPU-bound (batch, HPC)</td><td>Compute-optimized (C)</td><td>High CPU per dollar</td></tr><tr><td>In-memory DB, caching</td><td>Memory-optimized (R, X)</td><td>Large RAM per vCPU</td></tr><tr><td>ML, rendering</td><td>Accelerated (P, G - GPU)</td><td>GPU acceleration</td></tr><tr><td>Big data, warehouses</td><td>Storage-optimized (I, D)</td><td>High local disk throughput</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Beyond family, you choose vCPU/memory size and whether to scale <em>vertically</em> (bigger instance) or <em>horizontally</em> (more instances behind a load balancer). Horizontal scaling with an auto-scaling group is preferred for elasticity and fault tolerance.</p><h3>Storage requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Storage requirements</span> drive the storage <em>type</em> and <em>performance tier</em>. The first decision is block vs. file vs. object; the second is the performance/cost tier within that type. A database needs low-latency block storage with provisioned IOPS; an archive needs cheap, slow object storage:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Need</th><th>Choose</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>OS disk, database volume</td><td>Block, SSD, provisioned IOPS</td><td>EBS io2</td></tr><tr><td>Shared file system</td><td>File storage</td><td>EFS, Azure Files</td></tr><tr><td>Web assets, backups, big data</td><td>Object storage</td><td>S3 Standard</td></tr><tr><td>Rarely accessed archive</td><td>Cold/archive tier</td><td>S3 Glacier</td></tr></tbody></table><pre><code># A high-IOPS volume provisioned to a DB performance requirement\nresource \"aws_ebs_volume\" \"db_data\" {\n  availability_zone = var.az\n  size              = 500\n  type              = \"io2\"\n  iops              = 16000     # provisioned to meet the DB's IOPS target\n  encrypted         = true\n}</code></pre><h3>Network requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Network requirements</span> shape bandwidth, latency, topology, and connectivity. Latency-sensitive workloads push you toward a region close to users and possibly an edge/CDN layer; high east-west bandwidth pushes you toward placement groups or enhanced networking; private connectivity to on-prem dictates VPN vs. a dedicated circuit. The network requirement is also where region and availability-zone placement gets decided, since latency and data-residency both depend on geography.</p><h3>Right-sizing against the baseline</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Right-sizing</span> is the discipline of matching provisioned capacity to measured demand rather than to a guess or a legacy on-prem spec. Over-provisioning wastes money on idle resources; under-provisioning throttles the workload. The correct method is to capture a baseline - CPU, memory, IOPS, network throughput at p50 and p95 over a representative period - then pick the smallest instance and storage tier that comfortably covers the p95 with headroom for spikes. Cloud cost tools (AWS Compute Optimizer, Azure Advisor) recommend right-sizing moves from observed utilization, and elasticity means you can start conservative and scale out rather than buying peak capacity up front.</p><h3>Scaling models in detail</h3><p>Two scaling axes serve different needs. <span class='keyterm'>Vertical scaling</span> (scale up) replaces an instance with a larger one - simple, but bounded by the biggest instance available and usually requiring a restart. <span class='keyterm'>Horizontal scaling</span> (scale out) adds more instances behind a load balancer - effectively unbounded, fault-tolerant, and the foundation of cloud elasticity, but it requires the application to be stateless or to externalize state. Auto-scaling groups add and remove instances automatically on metrics or schedules, paying only for what demand requires.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Axis</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Limit</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Vertical (up)</td><td>Bigger instance</td><td>Max instance size</td><td>Stateful singletons, quick wins</td></tr><tr><td>Horizontal (out)</td><td>More instances + LB</td><td>Effectively unbounded</td><td>Stateless tiers, elasticity, HA</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Storage performance dimensions</h3><p>Storage requirements are multi-dimensional: <strong>capacity</strong> (gigabytes), <strong>IOPS</strong> (operations per second, the metric transactional databases care about), <strong>throughput</strong> (megabytes per second, the metric large sequential workloads care about), and <strong>latency</strong>. A misread here is a classic failure: provisioning a high-capacity but low-IOPS volume for a busy database starves it, while paying for provisioned IOPS on a cold archive wastes money. Match the dominant metric to the workload - random small reads/writes need IOPS, big streaming reads need throughput.</p><pre><code># A throughput-optimized volume for a streaming analytics job\nresource \"aws_ebs_volume\" \"analytics\" {\n  availability_zone = var.az\n  size              = 4000\n  type              = \"st1\"        # throughput-optimized HDD\n  throughput        = 500          # MB/s, the metric that matters here\n}</code></pre><h3>Network topology and connectivity choices</h3><p>Network provisioning also chooses the connectivity model. For private links to on-premises, a <span class='keyterm'>VPN</span> over the internet is cheap and quick but offers variable performance, while a <span class='keyterm'>dedicated circuit</span> (Direct Connect, ExpressRoute) provides consistent low latency and high bandwidth at higher cost and lead time. Within the cloud, content delivery networks and edge locations cut latency for geographically dispersed users, and placement groups or enhanced networking serve high east-west bandwidth between instances.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Connectivity</th><th>Performance</th><th>Cost</th><th>Use when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Site-to-site VPN</td><td>Variable (internet)</td><td>Low</td><td>Quick, modest bandwidth</td></tr><tr><td>Dedicated circuit</td><td>Consistent, high</td><td>High</td><td>Steady high-volume, low latency</td></tr><tr><td>CDN / edge</td><td>Low latency to users</td><td>Per-request</td><td>Global static/dynamic content</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div><p>Region choice is a multi-requirement decision: latency (network), data-residency (compliance), service availability (not every service exists in every region), and price (regions differ in cost). When these conflict, compliance usually wins.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Map the bottleneck to the family: CPU-bound = compute-optimized; large in-memory dataset = memory-optimized; GPU/ML = accelerated. For storage, low-latency transactional = block with provisioned IOPS; massive unstructured/cheap = object; archive = cold tier. Prefer horizontal scaling for elasticity and resilience.</p></div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[2].push(
  {heading:"Provisioning to Requirements: Availability, Security, Cost, Compliance", body:"<p>The remaining provisioning requirements are cross-cutting quality and business constraints: availability, performance, security, cost, and compliance. Each one reshapes the architecture you provision, and CV0-004 expects you to translate a stated requirement into the concrete redundancy, region, or configuration choice it demands.</p><h3>Availability requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Availability requirements</span> are usually expressed as an SLA target (e.g., 99.99% uptime) and drive <em>redundancy</em>. Higher targets demand spreading resources across multiple Availability Zones (for zone-level fault tolerance) or multiple regions (for regional disaster recovery), plus load balancing, auto-scaling, and automated failover. The required RTO/RPO determines how aggressive and costly the redundancy must be.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Availability target</th><th>Typical design</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Single instance</td><td>One AZ, no redundancy (dev/test)</td></tr><tr><td>~99.9%</td><td>Multi-AZ, load balanced, auto-scaling</td></tr><tr><td>~99.99%+</td><td>Multi-region, active-active or warm standby</td></tr></tbody></table><pre><code># Availability requirement -&gt; spread an ASG across multiple AZs\nresource \"aws_autoscaling_group\" \"web\" {\n  min_size            = 3\n  max_size            = 12\n  desired_capacity    = 3\n  vpc_zone_identifier = var.subnet_ids   # subnets in 3 separate AZs\n  health_check_type   = \"ELB\"\n}</code></pre><h3>Translating SLAs into RTO and RPO</h3><p>Availability requirements are usually paired with two recovery targets that drive the architecture's cost. <span class='keyterm'>Recovery time objective</span> (RTO) is how long the system may be down; <span class='keyterm'>recovery point objective</span> (RPO) is how much data loss is tolerable, measured in time. A near-zero RTO/RPO demands an active-active multi-region design with continuous replication - the most expensive pattern. A relaxed RTO of hours and RPO of a day can be met with nightly backups and a cold standby. Mapping the stated objectives to the cheapest design that meets them is the core skill.</p><table><thead><tr><th>RTO / RPO</th><th>DR pattern</th><th>Relative cost</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Hours / day</td><td>Backup and restore</td><td>Lowest</td></tr><tr><td>~1 hour / minutes</td><td>Pilot light</td><td>Low-medium</td></tr><tr><td>Minutes / seconds</td><td>Warm standby</td><td>High</td></tr><tr><td>Near zero / near zero</td><td>Active-active multi-region</td><td>Highest</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Performance requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Performance requirements</span> (throughput, IOPS, latency targets) drive instance sizing, storage tier, provisioned IOPS, caching layers, and CDN use. A latency SLO might justify an in-memory cache (ElastiCache) or edge delivery; a throughput target might justify a larger instance or read replicas. Performance and cost are in constant tension - over-provisioning meets the SLO but wastes money. The disciplined approach is to set explicit service-level objectives (e.g., p99 latency under 200 ms) and provision to meet them with measured headroom, then let auto-scaling absorb peaks rather than statically sizing for the worst case.</p><h3>Security requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Security requirements</span> dictate encryption (at rest and in transit), network isolation (private subnets, security groups, NACLs), identity controls (IAM least privilege), and key management. A requirement like \"data encrypted at rest with customer-managed keys\" maps directly to enabling encryption with a KMS CMK on every volume and bucket. Security requirements often constrain which services and regions are even permitted.</p><h3>Cost requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Cost requirements</span> impose a budget that shapes purchasing model and sizing. Levers include right-sizing to actual utilization, choosing reserved instances or savings plans for steady workloads, spot instances for interruptible work, auto-scaling to avoid paying for idle capacity, and selecting cheaper regions or storage tiers. The cost requirement is what forces the trade-offs among the other requirements - you rarely get maximum performance, availability, and security at minimum cost.</p><h3>Purchasing models compared</h3><p>The choice of <span class='keyterm'>purchasing model</span> can move the bill more than any sizing decision. <strong>On-demand</strong> pays full price per hour with no commitment - maximum flexibility, highest unit cost. <strong>Reserved instances / savings plans</strong> commit to one or three years for steep discounts on predictable baseline load. <strong>Spot instances</strong> use spare capacity at up to 90% off but can be reclaimed with little notice, suiting fault-tolerant batch and stateless workers. The standard pattern is to cover steady baseline with reservations, handle variable demand on-demand, and offload interruptible work to spot.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Discount</th><th>Commitment</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>On-demand</td><td>None</td><td>None</td><td>Spiky, unpredictable load</td></tr><tr><td>Reserved / savings plan</td><td>Large</td><td>1-3 years</td><td>Steady baseline</td></tr><tr><td>Spot</td><td>Largest</td><td>None (interruptible)</td><td>Batch, stateless workers</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Tagging and cost-allocation discipline underpins all of this: without tags identifying owner, environment, and cost center, a budget requirement cannot be enforced or attributed. Provisioning to a cost requirement therefore means not just choosing cheap resources but instrumenting them so spend is visible and accountable.</p><h3>Compliance requirements</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Compliance requirements</span> (HIPAA, PCI DSS, GDPR, FedRAMP, data residency) constrain region selection, which provider services are allowed, encryption and logging mandates, and tenancy (some regimes require dedicated hosts). Compliance frequently <em>overrides</em> cost and performance: a cheaper region or service is irrelevant if it is not authorized for the regulated data.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Requirement</th><th>Primary provisioning lever</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Availability</td><td>Multi-AZ/region redundancy, failover</td></tr><tr><td>Performance</td><td>Instance size, IOPS, caching, CDN</td></tr><tr><td>Security</td><td>Encryption, isolation, IAM, KMS</td></tr><tr><td>Cost</td><td>Right-sizing, reserved/spot, tiering</td></tr><tr><td>Compliance</td><td>Region, allowed services, tenancy</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A healthcare app must be 99.99% available, encrypt PHI at rest with managed keys, stay within a US-only region for HIPAA, and hold a fixed monthly budget. The architect provisions a multi-AZ auto-scaling deployment (availability) in a US region only (compliance), with KMS encryption on all stores (security), using reserved instances for the steady base load to honor the budget (cost). Compliance fixes the region before any cost optimization is even considered.</p></div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>When requirements conflict, compliance and security typically constrain the solution space first, then availability and performance shape redundancy and sizing, and cost decides among the remaining valid options. A stated SLA (99.9% vs 99.99%) is the clearest signal of how much multi-AZ/multi-region redundancy to provision.</p></div>"}
);
